n framework. Their work deflates stereotypes, promotes respect for cultural and ethnic minorities and gives a new dignity to subjects supposedly located on the margins of the Republic. Establishing a productive dialogue with Marianne Hirsch’s ground-breaking concept of postmemory, this volume provides a much-needed vocabulary for rethinking the intergenerational legacy of trans-Mediterranean immigrants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrench literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImmigrants in literature. 0aImmigrants in motion pictures. 0aImmigrants on television. 0aNorth AfricanszFrance. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aAbdellatif Kechiche.  aFrance.  aFrench heritage.  aImmigration.  aMaghreb.  aMaghrebi-French population.  aNorth Africa.  abeur literature.  acultural minorities.  aethnic minorities.  afiction.  afilm.  aharki.  aidentity.  aliterature.  amimetic powers.  amulticulturalism.  apost-coloniality.  apost-immigration population.  apostmemorial immigration.  apostmemory.  atelevision.  atrans-Mediterranean.  atransformative powers.1 aAbderrezak, Hakim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoutouba, Jimia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl Khoury, Mona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFache, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIreland, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaronde, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe Breton, Mireille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMach